1151":"1063–1151","1082–1163":"1082–1163","1040–Male":"1040–Deceased","1043–Female":"1043–Deceased","1154":"1154","1043":"1043","1163":"1163","1063":"1063","1151":"1151","before 1082":"before 1082","1040":"1040","1082":"1082","Longueville, Isle of Jersey, Channel Islands, England":"Longueville, Jersey","Channel Islands, England":"Channel Islands","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Duncan","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Scottish: from the Older Scots personal name <i>Dunecan</i>, itself from the traditional Irish royal name <i>Donnchad(h)</i>, derived from <i>donn</i> ‘brown-haired’ + <i>cath</i> ‘battle’. Judging by the Scots form, the Scottish Gaelic intermediary seems to have been understood as containing <i>ceann</i> ‘head’, as if the whole name meant ‘brown head’; compare sense 2. In Ireland the name was Anglicized as <i>Donagh</i> or <i>Donaghue</i>. Compare   Donahue  .","Irish: used as an Anglicized equivalent of Gaelic <b>Ó Duinnchinn</b> ‘descendant of <i>Donncheann</i>’, a byname composed of the elements <i>donn</i> ‘brown-haired man’ or ‘chieftain’ + <i>ceann</i> ‘head’."],"variants":[{"name":"Duncanson","meanings":["Scottish: from the Scottish personal name   Duncan   + <i>son</i> ‘son of Duncan’."]},{"name":"Dinkin","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Jewish Isador.","Jewish (eastern Ashkenazic): metronymic, with the addition of the Slavic possessive suffix <i>-in</i>, from the Yiddish female personal name <i>Dinke</i>, a hypocoristic form of Biblical <i>Dinah</i>, from Hebrew <i>dina</i> ‘judged, vindicated’.","Irish: shortened Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Ó Duinnchinn</b> (see   Duncan   2)."]},{"name":"Donkin","meanings":["English (Durham and Northumberland): northeastern English variant of Scottish   Duncan  ."]},{"name":"Donahue","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Irish Brendan, Aidan, Siobhan, Aileen, Conan, Fidelma, John Patrick, Kieran, Parnell.","Irish: shortened Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Ó Donnchadha</b> ‘descendant of <i>Donnchadh</i>’, a personal name (sometimes Anglicized as <i>Duncan</i> in Scotland), composed of the elements <i>donn</i> ‘brown-haired man’ or ‘chieftain’ + <i>cath</i> ‘battle’."]},{"name":"Dunkin","meanings":["Manx: variant of   Duncan  .","Irish (Fermanagh): Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Ó Duinnchinn</b> (see   Duncan  )."]}]},{"name":"Sarah","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Biblical name, borne by the wife of Abraham and mother of Isaac. According to the Book of Genesis, she was originally called <i>Sarai</i> (possibly meaning ‘contentious’ in Hebrew), but had her name changed by God to the more auspicious <i>Sarah</i> ‘princess’ in token of a greater blessing (Genesis 17:15, ‘And God said unto Abraham, As for Sarai thy wife, thou shalt not call her name Sarai, but Sarah shall her name be’). This has been one of the most enduringly popular girls' names."],"variants":[{"name":"Sara","meanings":["Variant of   Sarah .  This is the form used in the Greek of the New Testament (Hebrews 11:11)."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Sarah Duncan was born in 1063, in Longueville, Jersey, her father, George Duncan, was 24 and her mother, Mrs George Duncan Cameron, was 21. She married John Wright II before 1082, in Longueville, Jersey. They were the parents of at least 1 daughter. She died in 1154, in Longueville, Jersey, at the age of 91."},"et":{"1063–1154":"1063–1154","1063–1151":"1063–1151","1082–1163":"1082–1163","1040–Male":"1040–Surnud","1043–Female":"1043–Surnud","1154":"1154","1043":"1043","1163":"1163","1063":"1063","1151":"1151","before 1082":"enne 1082","1040":"1040","1082":"1082","Longueville, Isle of Jersey, Channel Islands, England":"Longueville, Jersey saar","Channel Islands, England":"Channel Islands"},"fi":{"1063–1154":"1063–1154","1063–1151":"1063–1151","1082–1163":"1082–1163","1040–Male":"1040–Kuollut","1043–Fem